                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 2071</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Hoover<br/>(Coauthor: Senator Umberg)<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 18, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to amend Sections 51928 and 51929 of the Education Code, relating to pupil instruction. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 2071, as amended, Hoover.
                          Pupil instruction: digital wellness.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law requires the State Department of Education, on or before January 1, 2024, to develop a plan to expand mental health instruction in California public schools.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the department, on or before January 1, 2028, to develop a plan to expand digital wellness instruction in California public schools, as provided.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.8336314360092989"><div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> (a) For purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) “Artificial intelligence” has the same meaning as defined in Section 33328.5 of the Education Code.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) “Digital wellness” means a state of well-being in which an individual uses technology in ways that support physical health, mental health, social connections, and overall quality of life, while minimizing potential harms.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) “Media literacy” means the ability to access, analyze, evaluate, create, and act using all forms
				of communication, including understanding how media messages are constructed, for what purposes, and with what effects.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Digital technology and artificial intelligence are increasingly integral to the daily lives, social interactions, and learning experiences of California’s youth.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Excessive or inappropriate use of digital media, social media platforms, and artificial intelligence-powered technologies can negatively impact mental health, contributing to anxiety, depression, sleep disorders, attention difficulties, body image issues, social isolation, and suicidal ideation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Youth face unique digital challenges, including cyberbullying, online harassment, exposure to harmful content, privacy violations, algorithmic manipulation, misinformation, and
				artificial intelligence-generated content that may be difficult to distinguish from reality.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Digital wellness education, including healthy technology use, critical media literacy, and understanding of artificial intelligence systems, is essential for youth to develop balanced relationships with technology and protect their mental and physical well-being.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) The intersection of digital technology and mental health requires explicit educational intervention to help pupils develop skills for healthy digital citizenship, self-regulation, and critical thinking.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(F) Education on digital wellness and media literacy complements and enhances mental health education by addressing a primary environmental
				factor affecting youth mental health in the 21st century.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) For the reasons described in subdivision (b), it is the intent of the Legislature in enacting this act to ensure that pupils in<font color="#B30000"><strike> middle school or</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> elementary school, middle school, and</i></font> high school have the opportunity to benefit from comprehensive education on digital wellness, media literacy, and the responsible use of emerging technologies, including artificial intelligence.</div></div></div><div id="s20.16754714851698305"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SEC. 2.</h3> Section 51928 of the Education Code is amended to read:</div><div><div id="id_E6DE6A05-23BC-461A-83CC-480C5921F072"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">51928.</h6> For purposes of this article, the following definitions apply:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(a) “Age appropriate” has the same meaning as defined in Section 51931.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) “Artificial intelligence” has the same meaning as defined in Section 33328.5.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) “Digital wellness” means a state of well-being in which an individual uses technology in ways that support physical health, mental health, social connections, and overall quality of life, while minimizing potential harms.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) “English learner” has the same meaning as defined in Section 51931.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) “Evidence-based” means verified or supported by research conducted in compliance with scientific methods and published in peer-reviewed journals, where appropriate, and recognized as accurate and objective by professional organizations and agencies with expertise in the mental health field.</div></p></div></div></div></div><div id="s30.6849099796463477"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SEC. 3.</h3> Section 51929 of the Education Code is amended to read:</div><div><div id="id_31D25804-DED5-4F3B-B0B4-7BA35A11CB62"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">51929.</h6> (a) On or before January 1, 2024, the department shall develop a plan to expand mental health instruction in California public schools.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) On or before January 1, 2028, the department shall develop a plan to expand digital wellness instruction in California public schools. This plan shall include all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Recommendations for age-appropriate<font color="#B30000"><strike> curriculum frameworks</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> instructional resources</i></font> for<font color="#B30000"><strike> middle schools</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
						elementary schools, middle schools,</i></font> and high schools.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Strategies for keeping curriculum current with rapidly evolving digital and artificial intelligence technology.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Guidance for schools with limited technology resources.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Family engagement and education components.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Assessment methods for evaluating instruction effectiveness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Strategies for ensuring adequate support and professional development opportunities for educators regarding digital wellness topics, including collaboration with technology companies, mental health
						organizations, and media literacy experts, as appropriate.</div></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
